<header>
<div id="instruction">
	Read the Writing Task and look carefully at the bar chart. Complete the report by choosing the word, phrase or number which best fits each gap.
</div>

</header>

  
<section id="body">

    <a id="clickme"><img class="imagetask" src="../media/btn_writingtask.jpg" mode="1" id="1001"/></a>
  <br/><br/><br/>
  <a id="visual"><img class="rightFloat" src="../media/AC_AW_002s.jpg" mode="1" id="1001"/></a>
  <div id="dropdown">
  <p>The chart compares the attendance of Canadians of different&#xA0; 
  <select id="q1">
  <option id="a1">incomes</option>
  <option id="a2">ages</option>
  <option id="a3">interests</option></select>
  &#xA0;at live arts performances. There is clearly a strong relationship between age and the sort of events people attend.</p>
  
  <p>The figures show that&#xA0; 
  <select id="q2">
  <option id="a4">almost half</option>
  <option id="a5">half</option>
  <option id="a6">just over half</option></select>
  &#xA0;of Canadian teenagers frequently go to live arts events and that they are almost&#xA0; 
  <select id="q3">
  <option id="a7">half</option>
  <option id="a8">twice</option>
  <option id="a9">three times</option></select>
  &#xA0;as likely to attend such performances as Canadians who are 60 or over. Not surprisingly, the greatest difference in attendance figures is for&#xA0; 
  <select id="q4">
  <option id="a10">opera</option>
  <option id="a11">theatrical performances</option>
  <option id="a12">pop concerts</option></select>.
  The 15 to 19 age group is almost&#xA0; 
  <select id="q5">
  <option id="a13">ten times</option>
  <option id="a14">twice</option>
  <option id="a15">five times</option></select>
  &#xA0;as likely as the over 60s to attend such concerts. Likewise, the proportion of Canadians who go to theatre, opera and&#xA0; 
  <select id="q6">
  <option id="a16">dance</option>
  <option id="a17">symphonic or classical music</option>
  <option id="a18">choral music</option></select>
  &#xA0;performances falls as age increases.</p>
  
  <p>In contrast, the proportion who go to classical and choral music performances rises as age increases. Approximately&#xA0; 
  <select id="q7">
  <option id="a19">1 in 4</option>
  <option id="a20">1 in 10</option>
  <option id="a21">1 in 3</option></select>
  &#xA0;Canadians who are 60 or over go to classical concerts. This percentage is almost&#xA0; 
  <select id="q8">
  <option  id="a22">as high</option>
  <option id="a23">twice as high</option>
  <option id="a24">three times as high</option></select>
  &#xA0;as that for teenagers.</p>
  
  <p>Attendance rates vary the least for theatre and opera performances. Only about&#xA0;
  <select id="q9">
  <option id="a25">a fifth</option>
  <option id="a26">a tenth</option>
  <option id="a27">a quarter</option></select>
  &#xA0;of all age groups attend the theatre frequently. Similarly, a very small&#xA0; 
  <select id="q10">
  <option id="a28">quantity</option>
  <option id="a29">percentage</option>
  <option id="a30">number</option></select>
  &#xA0;of any age group go to the opera regularly.</p>
  
  <p>In summary, audiences at Canadian performing arts events seem to be mainly young people attending plays or pop concerts.</p>

  <p class="linespace"></p>
  </div>
