<section id="fb1">
    <p class="feedbacktext">1. The title says 'by age group'.</p>
</section>

<section id="fb2">
    <p class="feedbacktext">2. 47.2 per cent, which is almost half.</p>
</section>

<section id="fb3">
    <p class="feedbacktext">3. 47.2 per cent for teenagers compared to almost 25 per cent for the oldest age group.</p>
</section>

<section id="fb4">
    <p class="feedbacktext">4. It's not surprising that pop concerts are much more popular with younger age groups.</p>
</section>

<section id="fb5">
    <p class="feedbacktext">5. Compare just over 7 per cent for the over-60s to nearly 35 per cent for teenagers.</p>
</section>

<section id="fb6">
    <p class="feedbacktext">6. As with pop music, dance performances are more popular with younger people.</p>
</section>

<section id="fb7">
    <p class="feedbacktext">7. 8.3 per cent, which is approximately 1 in 10.</p>
</section>

<section id="fb8">
    <p class="feedbacktext">8. Compare just over 8 per cent for the over-60s with just over 5 per cent for teenagers.</p>
</section>

<section id="fb9">
    <p class="feedbacktext">9. The percentages range from about 17 per cent for the over-60s to about 22 per cent for teenagers, which is about a fifth.</p>
</section>

<section id="fb10">
    <p class="feedbacktext">10. We don't normally use 'quantity' to refer to people.</p>
    <p class="feedbacktext">In fact, the chart doesn't tell us the actual numbers involved. We don't know if the numbers are small or large.</p>
</section>

